8, "total_tokens": 6108}, "id": "f026386d-0401-91de-b831-54b3eabd46ed"}, "input": {"input": ["# Cognitive Distortions and Their Subtypes\n\nThe community centers around the concept of cognitive distortions, which are irrational or exaggerated thought patterns contributing to anxiety disorders. Key entities include Cognitive Distortion, Selective Negative Attention, and Catastrophizing, with the latter two being specific types of cognitive distortions. The relationships between these entities highlight their interconnectedness and the broader implications for mental health.\n\n## Cognitive Distortion as the central concept\n\nCognitive Distortion is the central entity in this community, representing irrational or exaggerated thought patterns that contribute to anxiety disorders. This concept is foundational to understanding the other entities in the community, as it provides the context for their existence and significance. The degree of Cognitive Distortion is 3, indicating its importance in the community. [Data: Entities (61)]\n\n## Selective Negative Attention as a subtype\n\nSelective Negative Attention is a specific type of cognitive distortion where individuals focus excessively on negative aspects of their experiences. This entity is directly related to Cognitive Distortion, with a combined degree of 4, indicating a strong relationship. The focus on negative aspects can exacerbate anxiety disorders, making this entity significant in the community. [Data: Entities (62), Relationships (56)]\n\n## Catastrophizing as a subtype\n\nCatastrophizing is another specific type of cognitive distortion where individuals expect the worst possible outcome in a situation. Like Selective Negative Attention, Catastrophizing is directly related to Cognitive Distortion, with a combined degree of 4. This entity is significant because it can lead to heightened anxiety and stress, further impacting mental health. [Data: Entities (63), Relationships (57)]\n\n## Interconnectedness of cognitive distortions\n\nThe relationships between Cognitive Distortion and its subtypes, Selective Negative Attention and Catastrophizing, highlight the interconnectedness of these entities. This interconnectedness suggests that addressing one type of cognitive distortion may have implications for the others, making it important to consider the community as a whole when addressing mental health issues. [Data: Relationships (56, 57)]", "# PHOBIA and Its Diagnostic Pioneers\n\nThe community centers around PHOBIA, a type of anxiety disorder characterized by intense, irrational fear. Key entities include Le Camus, Marks, and Gelden, who contributed to the understanding and classification of phobias. The community also encompasses specific types of phobias such as School Phobia, Animal Phobia, Specific Situational Phobia, and Disease Phobia, all of which are subtypes of PHOBIA. The relationships between these entities highlight the historical and diagnostic evolution of phobias.\n\n## PHOBIA as the central entity\n\nPHOBIA is the central entity in this community, representing a type of anxiety disorder characterized by intense, irrational fear. This condition profoundly impacts individuals' daily lives, compelling them to alter their behavior to manage their overwhelming fear. The centrality of PHOBIA is evident in its relationships with other entities, including Le Camus, Marks, Gelden, and various specific types of phobias. [Data: Entities (96), Relationships (93, 95, 96, 2596, 2597, +more)]\n\n## Le Camus's early contributions\n\nLe Camus, an 18th-century figure, conducted systematic medical research on fear phenomena, which contributed to the early understanding of phobias. His work laid the groundwork for later diagnostic and classification systems. The relationship between Le Camus and PHOBIA highlights the historical evolution of the study of phobias. [Data: Entities (89), Relationships (93)]\n\n## Marks and Gelden's diagnostic system\n\nMarks and Gelden established the diagnostic and classification system for phobias in the 1960s. Their work was pivotal in the formal recognition and categorization of different types of phobias, providing a framework for understanding and treating these disorders. The relationships between Marks, Gelden, and PHOBIA underscore their significant contributions to the field. [Data: Entities (91, 92), Relationships (95, 96)]\n\n## Specific types of phobias\n\nThe community includes specific types of phobias such as School Phobia, Animal Phobia, Specific Situational Phobia, and Disease Phobia. These subtypes illustrate the diverse manifestations of PHOBIA, each characterized by intense fear of specific objects, environments, or situations. The relationships between PHOBIA and these specific types highlight the complexity and variety of phobic disorders. [Data: Entities (2275, 2276, 2277, 2278), Relationships (2596, 2597, 2598, 2599)]\n\n## Davidson's gender distribution study\n\nDavidson studied the gender distribution of phobias in 1993, contributing to the understanding of how phobias manifest differently across genders. This study adds another layer to the comprehensive understanding of phobias, emphasizing the importance of demographic factors in the study of anxiety disorders. [Data: Relationships (108)]", "# Phobia Research Community: Fyer, Kendler, and Davidson\n\nThis community centers around researchers Fyer, Kendler, and Davidson, who have made significant contributions to the study of phobias, particularly focusing on genetic factors, gender differences, and treatment methods. Their work is interconnected through their shared focus on phobias, with Fyer and Davidson both exploring different aspects of the condition, and Kendler extending the research to include generalized anxiety disorder. The community's impact lies in its contributions to understanding and treating phobias, which are prevalent anxiety disorders affecting daily functioning.\n\n## Fyer's focus on genetic factors in ph